Anthrax, Lesotho
----------------
Information received on [and dated] 17 Dec 2014 from Mrs Marosi Molomo, Director of Livestock Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Food Security, Department of Livestock Services, Maseru, Lesotho

Summary
Report type: Follow-up report No. 1 (Final report)
Date of start of the event: 26 Feb 2014 [not [1] above but an earlier outbreak; see 20140319.2342817]
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 26 Feb 2014
Report date: 17 Dec 2014
Date submitted to OIE: 17 Dec 2014
Date event resolved: 06 Mar 2014
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: June 2013
Manifestation of disease: Clinical disease
Causal agent: _Bacillus anthracis_
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country
Related reports: Immediate notification (19 Mar 2014)
Follow-up report No. 1 (17 Dec 2014)
Outbreaks: There are no new outbreaks in this report

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive

Control measures
Measures applied:
- Vaccination in response to the outbreak(s):
Administrative division / Species / Total Vaccinated / Details
BEREA / Cattle / 757 / none
- Disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s)
- No treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: No other measures

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

--
Communicated by
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This new outbreak in Maseru is distant to the south from the Berea outbreak reported in March 2014, and for which we just now have a belated vaccination report. The Maseru outbreak is in fact during this summer's season, while the earlier Berea outbreak was in last summer's season. Maseru had previous outbreaks in 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010 and 2013. Berea has had previous outbreaks in 2009, 2012 and 2013.

The recent outbreak in Mohale's Hoek is close to the SE border with South Africa, and might well reflect a cross-border ecology and epidemiology of that region, shared with its neighbour. The earlier known outbreak in Mohale's Hoek was in 2010 and 2011.

Over the years there have been not infrequent human cases, usually just a handful. But in 2008, there were 29 human cases with 3 deaths, and in 2012, 238 cases with 2 deaths. But this is to be expected if livestock outbreaks are treated retrospectively when they are noted officially. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3039912,178.]
